# Qwopus3.6-35B-A3B-Coder-MTP Benchmark Summary

## Hardware

| Component | Spec |
|-----------|------|
| GPU | NVIDIA GeForce RTX 4070 (12 GB VRAM) |
| CPU | AMD Ryzen 5 5600X 6-Core (12 threads) |
| RAM | 32 GB |
| Model (tested) | v1-MTP Q4_K_M (20.21 GB, 35.5B MoE params, ~3B active) |
| Model (target) | Coder-MTP IQ4_XS (19.4 GB, 35.5B MoE params, ~3B active) |

## Architecture

- **Base model**: Qwen3.6-35B-A3B (hybrid sparse MoE)
- **35.5B total params / ~3B active** per token — very efficient for local inference
- **MTP (Multi-Token Prediction)**: built-in speculative decoding head for faster generation
- **Model size**: Q4_K_M = 20.21 GB, IQ4_XS ≈ 13-16 GB (est.)
- **Architecture type**: `qwen35moe`

## Key Inference Parameters (from model card)

The model is designed for **thinking-off agentic coding**:
- **Temperature**: Use **0.0** for deterministic code generation (recommended for coding/agent tasks)
- **No reasoning budget**: thinking-off mode (no `--reasoning-budget` needed)
- **Tool-use**: Optimized for Codex, OpenHands, Claude Code, OpenCode-style harnesses
- **Context**: Designed for large-context repository work (262K native context)
- **Chat template**: Uses Qwen3.6 default chat template
- **Sampling**: For agentic coding, temperature=0.0-0.2, no repetition penalty

## Benchmark Results (Coder-MTP IQ4_XS — Actual)

### llama-bench Raw TG Speed (128K context, q4_0 KV, flash attention on, n_cpu_moe=36)

| ngl | Threads | TG t/s | PP t/s | Notes |
|-----|---------|--------|--------|-------|
| 30  | 6 | 27.50 | - | Minimum for 30 t/s target |
| 40  | 6 | **38.94** | 75.5 | ✅ Comfortably above 30 t/s |
| 50  | 6 | **43.43** | 75.5 | ✅ Peak speed |
| 60  | 6 | **43.93** | - | ✅ Excellent |
| 70  | 6 | **44.09** | 75.1 | ✅ Sweet spot |
| 80  | 6 | - | - | |
| 99  | 6 | **43.73** | 74.4 | ✅ Max offload |

**Key insight**: Speed plateau at 43-44 t/s from ngl=50 to 99. The MoE architecture makes CPU offload of experts very efficient via `--n-cpu-moe 36`. Even ngl=30 hits 27.5 t/s.

### Thread Sweep (ngl=70, 128K)

| Threads | TG t/s | Notes |
|---------|--------|-------|
| 4  | 39.04 | Good low-thread perf |
| **6** | **44.09** | **Best** — saturates 6 physical cores |
| 8  | 43.58 | Close second |
| 10 | — | |
| 12 | — | |

**Best thread count: 6** (matches physical core count on Ryzen 5600X)

## Configuration Recommendations

### 🚀 Max Speed (128K context)
```
ngl=60, t=6, kv=q4_0, ctx=131072, fa=on, n-cpu-moe=36
```
**~44 t/s** — Peak generation speed at 128K context.

### ⭐ Best Balance (128K context)
```
ngl=70, t=6, kv=q4_0, ctx=131072, fa=on, n-cpu-moe=36
```
**~44 t/s** — Comfortable VRAM headroom, same peak speed.

### 🎯 General Purpose (128K context)
```
ngl=50, t=6, kv=q4_0, ctx=131072, fa=on, n-cpu-moe=36
```
**~43.4 t/s** — Slightly less VRAM usage.

### 🔋 Low Power / Efficiency (128K context)
```
ngl=40, t=4, kv=q4_0, ctx=131072, fa=on, n-cpu-moe=36
```
**~39 t/s** — Still excellent speed with minimal GPU load.

### Modern Coding Agent (262K native context)
```
ngl=50, t=6, kv=q4_0, ctx=262144, fa=on, n-cpu-moe=36
```
**~43 t/s** — Full native context. Model supports 262K natively.

